      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_3",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "In this expression, h(i) (x)/i! is a polynomial in x with integer coefficients, so its value at an integer x is an integer.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12705882352941175,
          0.32606060606060605,
          0.49019607843137253,
          0.3703030303030303
        ],
        "order": 7
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_4",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "For x = 0, . . , − 1, we deduce that (This can also be deduced more directly using the bino- mial theorem.) Since we assumed h(x) and h(x + p) are distinct modulo p2, we conclude that h′(x) ≠ 0 (mod p). Since h′ is a polynomial with integer coef- ficients, we have h′(x) = h′(x + mp) (mod p) for any integer m, and so h′ (x) ≠ 0 (mod p) for all integers x.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12784313725490196,
          0.37454545454545457,
          0.36470588235294116,
          0.3896969696969697
        ],
        "order": 8
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0007",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005",
    "primary_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_15",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 2,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_15",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "B–6 In all solutions, let Fn,k be the number of k-limited per- mutations of {1, . . ., n}.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5231372549019608,
          0.3812121212121212,
          0.9184313725490196,
          0.4109090909090909
        ],
        "order": 9
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_16",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "First solution: (by Jacob Tsimerman) Note that any permutation is k-limited if and only if its inverse is k- limited. Consequently, the number of k-limited per- mutations of {1, ., n} is the same as the number of k-limited involutions (permutations equal to their in- verses) of { 1, . , n }.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5568627450980392,
          0.41454545454545455,
          0.9184313725490196,
          0.503030303030303
        ],
        "order": 10
      }
    ]
  },
