  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0009",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005",
    "primary_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_17",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_17",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "We use the following fact several times: the number of involutions of {1, . . .,n} is odd if n = 0, 1 and even oth- erwise. This follows from the fact that non-involutions come in pairs, so the number of involutions has the same parity as the number of permutations, namely n!.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5568627450980392,
          0.5066666666666667,
          0.9192156862745098,
          0.58
        ],
        "order": 12
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0010",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005",
    "primary_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_6",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 2,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_6",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Now for x = 0, ., p2 − 1 and y = 0, ., − 1, we write",
        "bbox": [
          0.12705882352941175,
          0.52,
          0.49019607843137253,
          0.5363636363636364
        ],
        "order": 13
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_7",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Thus h(x), h(x+ p2), . .,h(x+ (p − 1)p2) run over all of the residue classes modulo p3 congruent to h(x) mod- ulo p2. Since the h(x) themselves cover all the residue classes modulo p2, this proves that h(0), . . ., h(p3 − 1) are distinct modulo p3.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12705882352941175,
          0.5733333333333334,
          0.4894117647058824,
          0.6478787878787878
        ],
        "order": 14
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0011",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005",
    "primary_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_18",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 2,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_18",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "For n ≤ k + 1, all involutions are k-limited. By the pre- vious paragraph, Fn,k is odd for n = 0, 1 and even for n = 2, . ., k + 1.",
        "bbox": [
          0.556078431372549,
          0.5842424242424242,
          0.9192156862745098,
          0.6278787878787879
        ],
        "order": 15
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_19",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "For n > k + 1, group the k-limited involutions into classes based on their actions on k + 2, . . , n. Note that for C a class and σ ∈ C, the set of elements of A = {1, . . , k + 1} which map into A under σ depends only on C, not on σ. Call this set S(C); then the size of C is exactly the number of involutions of S(C). Conse- quently, |C| is even unless S(C) has at most one element. However, the element 1 cannot map out of A because we are looking at k-limited involutions. Hence if S(C) has one element and σ ∈ C, we must have σ(1) = 1. Since σ is k-limited and σ(2) cannot belong to A, we must have σ(2) = k + 2. By induction, for i = 3, . . ., k + 1, we must have σ(i) = k + i.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5568627450980392,
          0.6321212121212121,
          0.9192156862745098,
          0.8212121212121212
        ],
        "order": 16
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0012",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005",
    "primary_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_8",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 3,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_8",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Remark: More generally, the same proof shows that for any integers d,e > 1, h permutes the residue classes modulo pd if and only if it permutes the residue classes modulo pe. The argument used in the proof is related to a general result in number theory known as Hensel's lemma.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12627450980392158,
          0.6527272727272727,
          0.49019607843137253,
          0.7393939393939394
        ],
        "order": 17
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_9",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "B−5 The functions f(x) = x + n and f(x) = −x + n for any integer n clearly satisfy the condition of the problem; we claim that these are the only possible f .",
        "bbox": [
          0.09333333333333334,
          0.7490909090909091,
          0.4894117647058824,
          0.7933333333333333
        ],
        "order": 18
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_10",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Let q = a/b be any rational number with gcd(a, b) = 1 and b > 0. For n any positive integer, we have",
        "bbox": [
          0.12549019607843137,
          0.7975757575757576,
          0.4886274509803922,
          0.8272727272727273
        ],
        "order": 19
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0013",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005",
    "primary_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_20",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_20",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "If n < 2k + 1, this shows that no class C of odd cardi- nality can exist, so Fn,k must be even. If n ≥ 2k + 1, the classes of odd cardinality are in bijection with k- limited involutions of {2k + 2, . . ., n}, so Fn,k has the same parity as Fn−2k−1,k. By induction on n, we deduce the desired result.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5568627450980392,
          0.8254545454545454,
          0.92,
          0.9133333333333333
        ],
        "order": 20
      }
    ]
